        <comment>
  <id>65771221</id>
  <body><![CDATA[Yep. Agree. This book is overrated. I actually just read it a month or two ago, so it's still fresh in my mind. I feel like Forman didn't develop the characters or the overall story NEARLY enough. The entire premise begs for a book at least twice the size of the one she wrote, IMO. Think of all you could explore with this theme; I just don't understand how she could write such a short little nothing. <br /><br />Also, like you, I felt zip when Mia's family died. Forman didn't manipulate emotions the way she thought she was, and I am almost positive it's because she had not developed the characters enough before she executed them; we were not invested in them emotionally, because we had JUST met them. Therefore, how could we cry when they died? The most I felt was somber, but nary a tear blurred my vision, that's for sure. There's a sequel to this book, but I will only read it if I have nothing left to read. <br /><br />[Oh, and count me in the (teeny tiny) "I hate 'The Notebook' " club.]]]></body>
  
